messages.text: What have you always wanted to do, but have never done?
So we should be sixty percent in love by now.
Well, out of five questions, you‚Äôve asked three.
If you say so, math girl.
You got straight A‚Äôs in math too, didn‚Äôt you?
So what have you always wanted to do?
I want to see the cherry blossoms along the reservoir in Central Park.
What‚Äôs so special about cherry blossoms?
We had this beautiful tree when I was a kid.
And my sister and I played under it.
And give each other blossom bouquets.
You know it‚Äôs Spring now, right?
And Central Park isn‚Äôt far away.
There‚Äôs more to this than just a walk in the park.
You just sang for the first time since you were a kid.
It can‚Äôt be any harder than that, right?
Okay. So I‚Äôve never slow danced before.
Not even with some geeky guy friend at prom?
That I‚Äôm slow dancing in Central Park.
I‚Äôd love to see you in that dress, soaking wet.
Just when I was starting to like you‚Ä¶
You‚Äôd be lucky to get one percent.
Then I‚Äôd better ask you question number four.
See if I can improve that percentage.
The second to last question, huh?
Isn‚Äôt that a little dark for a love question?
Hey ‚Äî I didn‚Äôt choose the questions.
You gotta play around a little more.
I‚Äôll admit it felt good to sing.
I‚Äôd forgotten how much I loved music.
Still waiting on a serious answer‚Ä¶
My worst memory is when my dad walked out.
Yeah, it wasn‚Äôt just him leaving that was bad, but‚Ä¶
And all the fun, the laughter‚Ä¶the music‚Ä¶
So your mom never let you play music?
It wasn‚Äôt as simple as that.
She didn‚Äôt tell us not to play it.
But we knew it would remind her of Dad.
But I guess Mom was right.
He wasn‚Äôt ready to be a father.
So now you trust computer algorithms more than people?
Well ‚Äî your left arm is a good example.
Actually, lions aren‚Äôt all that loyal.
If they get hungry enough, they leave their packs and hunt for themselves.
I‚Äôll always take care of the people I love.
Even the people I eighty percent love.
So what‚Äôs your worst memory, motorcycle boy?
The day I found out my brother was missing.
Sorry ‚Äî I should have guessed that.
I knew something bad happened the moment I got the call.
By the time I got home‚Ä¶
Search and rescue already told my mom there was no chance he‚Äôd survived.
Every time I talk about my brother, you take my hand.
Using your brother‚Äôs memory like that.
Hey, Leo would be happy his memory is doing some good.
He always wanted a nice girl for his big brother.
The kind of girl I want to marry someday.
Let‚Äôs catch a cab to Central Park.
We‚Äôve got to be in love first.
That‚Äôs an easy problem to solve.
I just need to ask the last question.
You‚Äôre confident in these questions, aren‚Äôt you?
